snippet.textDisplay:
I have multiple sclerosis. My own immune system is fucked in a sense that it is attacking my own nerval system. Means that the virus is dangerous for me as well, yet i am sitting here and say, that i am not worried that much. I do have my thoughts about it, but i know that it is my own duty to be careful. I wash my hands each time i am in the bathroom, even if i did not use the toilet. I try to avoid public. I clean up after me. I try to avoid touching my face in any way if possible.

Should it get to me, i know what i have to do. But panic is the one thing that will just make you do mistakes. And through these mistakes you risk infecting yourself even faster.

So greetings from germany. Be careful out there, but don't panic.

snippet.textDisplay: Mark thank you for caring. This whole thing is fairly scary because there’s hardly anything we can do. Some people are overreacting about it but not everyone, sure we can be scared but we do not need to panic. It’s been hard bc every school in my state is closed until March 27 but I believe they should close it for longer because I’ve seen many other schools in other states close for over a month. It’s also been hard because the stores are completely empty and it’s hard, I hardly have anything at my home because we weren’t able to get anything due to people overreacting. My dads handicapped and it’s hard for him to go to the store alone but he did the other day but I don’t think he got enough to last us 30 days. It’s also upsetting because my school took away my spring break and is saying this is our spring break when it’s not, we have to do work, can barely even go outside and have to deal with peope freaking out. I think they should let us still have a week for spring break so I’m doing work one week but then one week I’m not doing work. I still think my school should at least close until April 13 or longer. I’ve even seen a school in a different state close for the rest of the year. It’s scary, but no need to overreact. There’s even no toilet paper at the store, not hardly anything else. I appreciate that you care mark, thank you, we will try our absolute best to stay safe and stay calm. :)

snippet.textDisplay: If you are not over or close to 50, you PERSONALLY have nothing to worry about. Personally. However, the disease is highly contagious and if you or a loved one, is over or close to the age of 50, or is immunocompromised, you should still try not to get it, not for your sake, but theirs. The coronavirus globally has a 3.7% death rate, fluctuating higher and lower but I’ve seen it stay just about around there mainly. 76% of those deaths are people over 50. Less than 1% are people under 20. Despite this, over half the deaths of the older generation are speculated to have been able to have been prevented if said younger people had not transferred it. People under 30 reading this, you are our frontline against this disease and at the same time, you are what we need to protect the most to prevent further harm. Please just take care to stay away from sick folks, wash your hands, shower regularly, and, should you start coughing and sneezing and getting nausea, joint pain, diarrhea or vomitting, stay away from those more vulnerable. That’s all I have to say, thank you.

snippet.textDisplay: Also just to let people know, and this is information I got from reading what WHO (the World Health Organization) has said about it. Young people are still at risk of serious symptoms from hCoV-19. Older individuals or people with compromised immune systems are more likely, key words, more likely to develop serious complications. That does not mean that young people are immune from being killed. Do not panic, but do not take this virus lightly.  Also prior to this video I had actually went to the WHO website and the info they have about hCoV-19, including symptoms and various important facts, are under the “Your Questions Answered” tab. I would highly recommend people view these. Also know that some of this data is not set in stone fact, this is a new virus and scientists are learning all they can about it, but it takes time to do so. WHO and the CDC will update the pages with anything new found but keep this all in mind
